# gjoa-patch:
#   baseline-firefox: 151.0.1
#   touches:
#     - third_party/sqlite3/src/moz.build
#
Enable SQLite FTS5 in the bundled SQLite build.

Stock Firefox compiles its bundled SQLite (currently 3.51.3) without
the FTS5 full-text-search extension. The FTS5 source ships in the
amalgamation but is gated by `SQLITE_ENABLE_FTS5`, so attempting to
`CREATE VIRTUAL TABLE ... USING fts5(...)` from chrome JS or storage
APIs returns "no such module: fts5".

Gjoa wants FTS5 available for in-browser full-text indexing (history,
bookmarks, tab snapshots). Patch the third_party/sqlite3/src/moz.build
to define `SQLITE_ENABLE_FTS5 = 1` so the extension gets linked into
libsqlite3.

We do NOT enable FTS3 — it's the legacy extension; FTS5 supersedes it.

diff --git a/third_party/sqlite3/src/moz.build b/third_party/sqlite3/src/moz.build
--- a/third_party/sqlite3/src/moz.build
+++ b/third_party/sqlite3/src/moz.build
@@ -135,6 +135,9 @@ DEFINES['SQLITE_DEFAULT_JOURNAL_SIZE_LIMIT'] = 1572864
 # Thunderbird/Mail uses the FTS3 extension, but it's not using enhanced query
 # syntax (SQLITE_ENABLE_FTS3_PARENTHESIS) yet.
 if CONFIG["MOZ_THUNDERBIRD"] or CONFIG["MOZ_SUITE"]:
     DEFINES['SQLITE_ENABLE_FTS3'] = 1

+# Gjoa: enable FTS5 for in-browser full-text indexing.
+DEFINES['SQLITE_ENABLE_FTS5'] = 1
+
 # The carray extension is part of the amalgamation but disabled by default.
 DEFINES['SQLITE_ENABLE_CARRAY'] = 1
